	id="Expla_OrientationSame">
	<title>Same Orientation: Explanation</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>Wait a minute! If we want to test whether two ordered bases <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex> and <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex> determine the same or opposite orientations of <latex>V</latex>, how do we know whether we need to convert from <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>-coordinates to <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>-coordinates or vice versa?</para>
			<para>Answer: It does not matter! The determinants of both matrices have the same sign. To see this, we just need to recall that </para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>C_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}} = \left( C_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} \right)^{-1}</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>Because then we compute</para>
			<computation>
				<left>+1</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\det( C_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}) \cdot \det( C_{\EuScript{B} \EuScript{C}} )^{-1}</right>
				<left></left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\det( C_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}) \cdot \det( C_{\EuScript{C} \EuScript{B}} )</right>
			</computation>
			<para>So the two matrices have the same sign.</para>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>